10:34.033 --> 10:37.136 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
All parents would get 12 weeks
of paid leave.

10:37.170 --> 10:41.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Child care costs would be kept
to 10 percent
of the family's income for most
families,

10:41.908 --> 10:45.378 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
though Clinton hasn't shown
exactly how she'd
achieve that.

10:45.411 --> 10:49.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And she'd pay for it all by
raising taxes
on the wealthy.

10:49.148 --> 10:54.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Clinton would also use those
taxes to make
preschool universal starting at
4 years old.

10:54.420 --> 10:57.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON (D),
Presidential Candidate:
We have to make it easier to be
good workers,

10:57.156 --> 11:00.460 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
good parents, and good
caregivers, all at
the same time.

11:00.493 --> 11:04.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: This is further
than Clinton
went just two years ago on
mandatory paid

11:04.998 --> 11:08.668 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
leave, when she told CNN it was
too soon politically.

11:08.701 --> 11:10.570 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But now things have changed.

11:10.603 --> 11:15.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Both presidential nominees are
pushing for
paid family leave at the same
time, and perhaps

11:15.041 --> 11:16.776 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with good reason.

11:16.809 --> 11:21.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Polling shows that paid family
leave gets
the support of over 70 percent
of Americans

11:21.414 --> 11:26.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
over age 40, and that's the same
group that
has the highest turnout in
elections.

11:26.452 --> 11:31.891 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Lisa
Desjardins.

11:31.925 --> 11:42.835 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The latest national
polls show
a tightening in the race to the
White House,

11:42.869 --> 11:45.905 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
especially in key states like
Ohio and Florida.

11:45.939 --> 11:50.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when it comes down to it,
winning in November
will depend on which candidate
has a viable

11:50.677 --> 11:53.846 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
path to 270 electoral votes.

11:53.880 --> 11:59.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more, we're joined by John
Brabender,
Republican strategist and chief
creative officer

11:59.052 --> 12:04.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for BrabenderCox, a political
media firm,
and Bill Burton, former deputy
White House

12:04.390 --> 12:10.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
press secretary under President
Obama and
currently California managing
director for

12:10.897 --> 12:12.699 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SKDKnickerbocker.

12:12.732 --> 12:17.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
John Brabender, give us a map,
give us a tour
of what it takes for Donald
Trump to get to

12:17.570 --> 12:19.072 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
270.

12:19.105 --> 12:19.539 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN BRABENDER, Republican
Strategist: Well,
I'm going to oversimplify it

12:19.572 --> 12:21.007 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
GWEN IFILL: OK.

12:21.040 --> 12:22.508 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN BRABENDER: You first start
by winning
every state Mitt Romney won.

12:22.542 --> 12:23.509 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

12:23.543 --> 12:25.311 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Is that possible?

12:25.345 --> 12:26.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN BRABENDER: The tough one,
probably, if
there is one, it's probably
North Carolina.

12:26.980 --> 12:28.748 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That will be a battleground.

12:28.781 --> 12:32.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That doesn't get you anywhere
near 270, because
Mitt Romney wasn't anywhere near
270.

12:32.318 --> 12:34.854 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, there's two different paths
you can go.

12:34.887 --> 12:40.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You win a whole bunch of small
states and
cobble them together, which is
almost impossible.

12:40.960 --> 12:45.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To me, the logical path then is
where could
have Romney maybe have won and
didn't?

12:45.298 --> 12:47.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And you look at Ohio, Florida.

12:47.934 --> 12:49.902 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You're still not there.

12:49.936 --> 12:52.405 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now you have got to win either
Pennsylvania
or Michigan.

12:52.438 --> 12:57.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think Pennsylvania is
probably a little
bit more doable than Michigan,
but, again,

12:57.210 --> 13:00.079 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
neither one of those states have
the Republicans
won since 1988.

13:00.113 --> 13:04.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Bill Burton, take
that map and
add what you would think that
Hillary Clinton

13:04.550 --> 13:06.285 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
needs to get to 270.

13:06.319 --> 13:08.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BILL BURTON, Former Deputy White
House Press
Secretary: Well, I think you
start in the

13:08.321 --> 13:10.189 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
same place.

13:10.223 --> 13:13.626 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You look at the states Obama won
and wonder,
well, where would Hillary
Clinton have a problem

13:13.660 --> 13:16.229 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and where does Donald Trump have
problems?

13:16.262 --> 13:20.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the truth is, Donald Trump
is not showing
strength in any of the big
states that he

13:20.800 --> 13:23.469 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
would need in order to actually
get to 270.

13:23.503 --> 13:26.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Hillary Clinton is showing
herself to
be remarkably stable in all the
states that

13:26.773 --> 13:28.708 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
she needs.

13:28.741 --> 13:31.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I think that Florida, Ohio,
Michigan, Pennsylvania,
all those states actually look
pretty good

13:31.778 --> 13:33.613 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for Hillary Clinton right now.

13:33.646 --> 13:38.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And while Donald Trump is
showing some strength
in places like Iowa, it's just
not enough

13:38.484 --> 13:42.088 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to get him close to getting the
electoral
votes that he needs to win.

13:42.121 --> 13:46.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: John Brabender, we
know that he
did incredibly well in the
primaries.

13:46.225 --> 13:48.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We didn't expect Donald Trump to
do as well
as he did.

13:49.028 --> 13:52.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Can he use that megaphone or
alter it in some
way to have it apply in the
general election?

13:52.999 --> 13:54.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN BRABENDER: I think to some
degree.

13:54.133 --> 13:55.568 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Pennsylvania is a good example.

13:55.601 --> 13:58.638 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He won every one of the 67
counties.

13:58.671 --> 14:01.941 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Pennsylvania might be a
parochial state, but
it's not a homogeneous state.

14:01.974 --> 14:05.478 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, even among just Republican
voters, to
be able to pull that off, when
you have very

14:05.511 --> 14:09.082 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
moderate voters on one side of
the state and
more conservative in the middle,
shows that

14:09.115 --> 14:11.184 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
he has very, very broad support.

14:11.217 --> 14:14.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The second thing, in fairness to
the Trump
people, if you look at the most
recent numbers,

14:15.021 --> 14:19.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they're actually doing well in
Ohio, winning,
winning in a lot of polls in
Florida, and

14:19.692 --> 14:22.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
now Pennsylvania and Michigan
have both tightened.

14:22.328 --> 14:24.597 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're not ahead, but they have
tightened.

14:24.630 --> 14:26.399 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And that's a good trend.

14:26.432 --> 14:29.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Bill Burton, one of
the things
that Democrats say is that
Donald Trump gets

14:29.435 --> 14:33.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a lot of free media and that
that's a disadvantage
for Hillary Clinton.

14:33.539 --> 14:36.275 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can the free media lift him to
where he needs
to be?

14:36.309 --> 14:37.910 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Isn't that a potential threat to
her?

14:37.944 --> 14:41.114 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BILL BURTON: Well, I do have to
give their
campaign a little bit of credit.

14:41.147 --> 14:44.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Monica Langley has a great piece
in The Wall
Street Journal today about how
they're trying

14:44.851 --> 14:49.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to create different kinds of
moments for Donald
Trump, as opposed to just him
shouting at

14:49.422 --> 14:51.190 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
rallies.

14:51.224 --> 14:53.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're trying to get him in
classrooms, and
in churches, and in diners and
places where

14:53.960 --> 14:56.262 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he can make a more personal
connection.

14:56.295 --> 15:02.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, obviously, the strategy has
its setbacks,
as you saw today, Donald Trump
in a church

15:02.568 --> 15:06.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
getting interrupted by the
pastor because
he started attacking Hillary
Clinton.

15:06.239 --> 15:10.743 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think that if he does
really want to
make gains, if he does want to
find a path

15:10.777 --> 15:16.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to those voters who are in the
middle, then
he needs to do different things
than just

15:16.215 --> 15:17.650 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
do these rallies.

15:17.683 --> 15:19.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, you know, I think he's
actually doing
a pretty good job of that.

15:19.852 --> 15:23.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's still pretty limited in the
effect that
he can have because he so
disqualified himself

15:23.790 --> 15:27.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with such a large number of
voters that I
don't think that there is an
actual a path

15:27.493 --> 15:29.295 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to victory for him.

15:29.328 --> 15:32.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he is at least doing a
better -- engaging
in a better strategy than he had
previously.

15:32.732 --> 15:34.634 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: But, John, isn't
there a reason
for that?

15:34.667 --> 15:39.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That we see him in a church in
Detroit, Michigan
not a state that he's
necessarily competing

15:40.006 --> 15:45.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in, that we see him bring forth
the child
care program, isn't that to try
to address

15:45.411 --> 15:47.380 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the issues that Bill Burton is
talking about?

15:47.413 --> 15:51.651 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN BRABENDER: Well, I think
what it's to
do is to make him more likable.

15:51.684 --> 15:54.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here's the biggest problem I
think Donald
Trump has.

15:54.153 --> 15:58.825 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's not getting enough votes
today of the
people who already say they
don't like Hillary

15:58.858 --> 15:59.826 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Clinton.

15:59.859 --> 16:00.993 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And so I agree with Bill.

16:01.027 --> 16:02.728 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I agree with the pastor.

16:02.762 --> 16:05.498 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't think Donald Trump has
to be out there
making the case against Hillary
Clinton.

16:05.531 --> 16:07.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think people have known her 24
years.

16:07.567 --> 16:09.702 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How you feel about her, you feel
about her.

16:09.735 --> 16:13.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What they're still unsure about,
particularly
some moderate Republicans, we
know gender

16:13.472 --> 16:17.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there is difference, I think
Donald Trump
has to seal the deal by letting
people feel

16:17.243 --> 16:18.945 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
comfortable to vote for him.

16:18.978 --> 16:22.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Bill, you used to
work with David
Plouffe, who ran the Obama
campaign.

16:22.782 --> 16:28.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he said that -- I think it
was yesterday
-- he said this depends on who's
showing up,

16:28.154 --> 16:32.992 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the composition of the voters
that everyone
is fighting for.

16:33.025 --> 16:36.762 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
What do you think the
composition has to be
in order for Hillary Clinton to
win?

16:36.796 --> 16:40.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BILL BURTON: Well, something
that is interesting
about the current polling is
that, as you

16:40.399 --> 16:45.338 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
watch Hillary's numbers
fluctuate, part of
the reason that they are is
because the Obama

16:45.371 --> 16:52.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
coalition, younger voters,
African-American
voters, Latino voters, they're
not showing

16:52.111 --> 16:55.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up in as large a number for her
as they did
for President Obama.

16:56.015 --> 16:59.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for that reason, I actually
think that
her numbers are artificially
low.

16:59.852 --> 17:04.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that, at the end of the
day, those
voters are going to join ranks,
and it is

17:04.590 --> 17:06.592 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to help propel Hillary
Clinton to victory.

17:06.626 --> 17:09.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: We have seen -- I'm
going to stay
with you for a moment, Bill,
because we have

17:09.595 --> 17:14.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
seen in the last few days a big
debate over
the deplorables comment that
Hillary Clinton

17:14.767 --> 17:16.168 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
made the other night.

17:16.202 --> 17:19.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I wonder if part of that
debate isn't
about this very issue.

17:19.872 --> 17:26.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How do you win over the people
either who
are offended by portions of the
Trump coalition,

17:26.445 --> 17:30.950 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or how does Trump, in turn, tar
her as being
intolerant?

17:30.983 --> 17:32.485 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Isn't that about part of this?

17:32.518 --> 17:36.188 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BILL BURTON: I think that that
conversation
is happening along the edges.

17:36.222 --> 17:39.825 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't think that the folks who
are in the
middle look at the conversation
over whether

17:39.859 --> 17:43.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or not Donald Trump's campaign
is racist or
whether or not Hillary Clinton
should use

17:43.362 --> 17:48.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that term to describe some of
his supporters
made sense, I don't think that
the folks in

17:48.301 --> 17:49.936 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the middle are looking at that
debate.

17:49.969 --> 17:53.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think they're more looking at
these two
candidates.

17:53.139 --> 17:57.410 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a band of voters with which
neither candidate
has very high approval ratings.

17:57.443 --> 18:01.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they're trying to make up
their mind on
who has a better plan for the
economy, whose

18:01.948 --> 18:04.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
presidency would more positively
impact my
life?

18:04.517 --> 18:09.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that debate happens
sort of among
people who have already made up
their minds.

18:09.155 --> 18:11.090 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: What do you think
about that,
John Brabender?

18:11.123 --> 18:13.025 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN BRABENDER: Well, I agree.

18:13.059 --> 18:15.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sometimes, we all go on these
shows and we
have this debate over
deplorable, not deplorable.

18:15.995 --> 18:19.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's not what people
around their dining
room table are talking about at
night.

18:19.732 --> 18:24.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the things Trump has done
is tie into
particularly what would be the
sons and daughters

18:24.503 --> 18:30.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Reagan Democrats in places
like Ohio, Pennsylvania,
Wisconsin, Michigan, who are
voting for him

18:30.376 --> 18:34.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because they feel both parties
left them on
the economic battlefield.

18:34.547 --> 18:38.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They feel Washington doesn't
understand their
lives anymore, and they feel
that even though

18:38.551 --> 18:42.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Donald Trump might make a
mistake with what
he says from time to time, they
see that as

18:42.521 --> 18:47.626 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
authenticity and maybe somebody
who will truly
pay attention to them, because
they feel ignored.

18:47.660 --> 18:50.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And there are,
briefly, enough
of those people to get 270 for
Donald Trump?

18:50.963 --> 18:52.732 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN BRABENDER: Well, here's the
thing.

18:52.765 --> 18:56.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a state like Pennsylvania,
the paradox
is, to win, you have to get the
conservative

18:56.402 --> 19:00.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Democrats in the west, but you
still have
to do well with the
collar-county moderates

19:00.673 --> 19:02.108 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the east.

19:02.141 --> 19:04.810 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Romney did fine with the
moderates, but not
the conservative Democrats.

19:04.844 --> 19:07.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Trump is doing well with the
conservative
Democrats.

19:07.546 --> 19:09.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now Trump has to seal the deal
with the moderates
in the east.

19:10.016 --> 19:12.018 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Fifty-six days,
guys.

19:12.051 --> 19:15.187 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
John Brabender, Bill Burton,
thank you both
very much.

19:15.221 --> 19:20.259 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BILL BURTON: Thank you.

19:20.292 --> 19:25.331 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN BRABENDER: Thank you.

19:25.364 --> 19:28.734 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

19:28.768 --> 19:36.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
Uber debuts self-driving
